18 some ability to pay some or all of but not the ability to pay the
19 full amount, the court financial obligations, the court may order
20 any of the following conditions for payment:
21 a. payment in full,
22 b. payment in installments,
23 c. financial incentive under a set of conditions
24 determined by the court, or
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 8

1 d. community service in lieu of payment; provided, the
2 defendant shall receive credit for no less than two
3 times the amount of the minimum wage specified
4 pursuant to state law for each hour of community
5 service.
6 2. Any shall reduce the amount owed or impose payment in part,
7 and may order community service in lieu of payment, establish an
8 installment plan consistent with the financial capacity of the
9 defendant who fails to comply with the terms of the payment plan
10 ordered by the court shall be considered delinquent and the court
11 may issue either a cost cite and release warrant or a cost arrest
12 warrant, or order the defendant to participate in another
13 alternative program.
14 F. D. If at any later time, the court determines that a waiver
15 of any of the court receives credible evidence that the financial
16 obligations is warranted circumstances of the defendant satisfy one
17 or more of the criteria in paragraph 3 of subsection B of this
18 section, or that the circumstances described in subsection C of this
19 section apply, or otherwise demonstrate inability to pay the full
20 remaining balance, the court shall apply the same percentage
21 reduction equally to all reopen the determination and may reduce or
22 waive the remaining fines, court costs, fees, and assessments,
23 excluding restitution accordingly.
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 9

1 G. E. 1. A defendant is considered delinquent in the payment
2 of court financial obligations under the following circumstances:
3 a. when the total amount due has not been paid by the due
4 date, or
5 b. when no installment payments have been received in the
6 most recent ninety-day period.
7 2. The court clerk shall periodically review cases for
8 delinquency at least once every six (6) months and, upon identifying
9 a delinquent defendant, notify the court which shall, within ten
10 (10) days thereafter, set a cost hearing for the court to determine
11 if the defendant is able to pay pursuant to the criteria set forth
12 in this section. The cost hearing shall be set within forty-five
13 (45) days of the issuance of the summons. The hearing shall be set
14 on a date that shall allow the court clerk to issue a summons
15 fourteen (14) days prior to the cost hearing. Defendants shall
16 incur no additional fees associated with the issuance of the
17 summons.
18 3. At least fourteen (14) days prior to the cost hearing, the
19 court clerk shall issue one summons to the defendant to be served by
20 United States mail to the mailing address of the defendant on file
21 in the case, substantially as follows:
22 SUMMONS
23 You are ORDERED to appear for a COST HEARING at a specified
24 time, place, and date to determine if you are financially able to
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 10

1 pay the fines, costs, fees, or assessments or an installment due in
2 Case No.__________.
3 YOU MUST BE PRESENT AT THE HEARING.
4 At any time before the date of the cost hearing, you may contact
5 the court clerk and pay the amount due or request in writing or in
6 person prior to the court date, that the hearing be rescheduled for
7 no later than thirty (30) days after the scheduled time.
8 THIS IS NOT AN ARREST WARRANT. However, if you fail to appear
9 for the cost hearing or pay the amount due, the court may issue a
10 WARRANT and may refer the case to a court cost compliance liaison
11 which will cause an additional administrative fee of up to thirty-
12 five percent (35%) to be added to the amount owed and may include
13 additional costs imposed by the court.
14 4. Referrals to the court cost compliance program as provided
15 in subsection L J of this section shall be made as follows:
16 a. courts shall refer a case to the court cost compliance
17 program upon the issuance of a cost arrest warrant,
18 b. courts may refer a case to the court cost compliance
19 program upon the issuance of a cost cite and release
20 warrant, or
21 c. courts may refer a case to the court cost compliance
22 program without the issuance of a warrant; provided,
23 the defendant is delinquent and has had sufficient
24 notice and opportunity to have a cost hearing.
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 11

1 5. A municipal court, in lieu of mailing the summons provided
2 for in this subsection, may give the summons to the defendant in
3 person at the time of sentencing or subsequent appearance of a
4 specific date, time, and place, not fewer than thirty (30) days nor
5 more than one hundred twenty (120) days from the date of sentencing
6 to appear for a cost hearing if the court financial obligations
7 remain unpaid.
8 H. F. 1. If a defendant is found by a law enforcement officer
9 to have an outstanding cost cite and release warrant, the law
10 enforcement officer shall issue a Warning/Notice to appear within
11 ten (10) thirty (30) days of release from detention on the warrant
12 to the court clerk of the court in which the court financial
13 obligations are owed. If the officer has the necessary equipment,
14 the officer shall immediately transmit the Warning/Notice
15 electronically to the court clerk of the court in which the court
16 financial obligations are owed. The law enforcement officer shall
17 not take the defendant into custody on the cite and release warrant.
18 If the law enforcement officer is unable to transmit the
19 Warning/Notice electronically to the court clerk, the officer shall
20 inform the appropriate department staff member within the agency of
21 the law enforcement officer of the Warning/Notice within five (5)
22 days. The department staff member shall then promptly notify the
23 law enforcement agency in the jurisdiction that issued the warrant
24 electronically who shall promptly notify the court clerk. The
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 12

1 elec tronic communication shall be treated as a duplicate original
2 for all purposes in any subsequent hearings before the appropriate
3 court.
4 2. If the defendant reports to the office of the court clerk
5 within the ten (10) thirty (30) days, the court clerk shall:
6 a. inform the court of the Warning/Notice to the
7 defendant and contact,
8 b. schedule a cost hearing pursuant to applicable local
9 court rule, and
10 c. submit the warrant to the court for recall pending the
11 cost hearing.
12 3. If the defendant fails to report to the office of the court
13 clerk within the ten (10) thirty (30) days, the court may issue a
14 cost arrest warrant for the arrest of the defendant.
15 4. Following an arrest on a cost arrest warrant, the defendant
16 must be released after seventy-two (72) twenty-four (24) hours in
17 custody, not including weekends. The defendant may be released
18 prior to seventy-two (72) twenty-four (24) hours if:
19 a. the custodian is presented with proof of payment in
20 the amount of One Hundred Dollars ($100.00) to each
21 jurisdiction where the court financial obligations are
22 owed and the new cost hearing date is provided,
23
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 13

1 b. the court releases the defendant on the defendant's
2 own recognizance and a new cost hearing date is
3 provided, or
4 c. the court conducts a cost or willfulness hearing, as
5 appropriate, pursuant to the provisions of this
6 section and determines the defendant should be
7 released.
8 5. The provisions for issuing a separate summons described in
9 subsection G E of this section shall not apply to a municipal court
10 if the municipal court has previously provided actual personal
11 notice to the defendant of an opportunity for a cost hearing. If
12 such notice was given and the defendant fails to appear, the
13 municipal court may issue either a cost cite and release warrant or
14 a cost arrest warrant.
15 6. All warrants for failure to appear at a cost hearing or for
16 failure to pay court financial obligations which have been issued
17 prior to the effective date of this act and which remain unserved,
18 shall be treated as cost cite and release warrants. All warrant
19 fees assessed for warrants for failure to appear at a cost hearing
20 or for failure to pay court financial obligations issued prior to
21 the effective date of this act shall remain in effect unless waived
22 by the court.
23 I. G. Supporting documents in a motion or affidavit for relief
24 from court financial obligation debt or any documents taken into
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 14

1 evid ence during a cost hearing or willfulness hearing shall not be
2 viewable by the public on a court-controlled website.
3 J. H. 1. After a cost hearing where a defendant is found able
4 to pay a court financial obligation, either in whole or in part, and
5 then becomes delinquent in that payment, a court may conduct a
6 willfulness hearing at any time beginning immediately after a cost
7 hearing has been held and a decision rendered on the court financial
8 obligations. Findings of a defendant's prior ability to pay may be
9 considered as evidence of ability to pay or willfulness at the
10 hearing. The requirements of this paragraph shall not be construed
11 to prohibit the court from holding subsequent cost hearings on the
12 same court financial obligations.
13 2. At a willfulness hearing, the court shall evaluate the
14 following:
15 a. whether a cost hearing has been held previously where
16 evidence relating to ability to pay was presented and
17 the court found the defendant was able to pay the
18 court financial obligations, either in whole or in
19 part,
20 b. whether there is any new evidence of ability to pay
21 not previously considered or a change in circumstances
22 since the cost hearing,
23
24
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 15

1 c. whether the defendant was afforded sufficient time and
2 opportunity to fulfill the obligation to pay the court
3 financial obligations,
4 d. whether the defendant made any efforts to satisfy the
5 court financial obligations, and
6 e. whether there are any other relevant facts or
7 circumstances.
8 3. After a finding of willful failure to pay court financial
9 obligations, the court may impose a jail sentence pursuant to
10 Section 101 of Title 28 of the Oklahoma Statutes. A jail sentence
11 may be imposed only under the following circumstances:
12 a. the hearing is conducted on the record pursuant to the
13 rules promulgated by the Court of Criminal Appeals,
14 and
15 b. the defendant is represented by counsel or expressly
16 waives his or her right to counsel.
17 4. If a jail sentence is imposed, the court may grant credit
18 for any time already served. At any time after incarceration, the
19 jail sentence may be satisfied upon payment in full of the
20 outstanding balance with credit for any time already served.
21 K. The district court or municipal court, within one hundred
22 twenty (120) days from the date upon which the person fails to
23 comply with the financial obligation as ordered by the court or
24 fails to appear for the offered cost or willfulness hearing, may, if
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 16

1 the defendant has previously been notified of the possibility of a
2 suspension, send notice of nonpayment of any court-ordered financial
3 obligation for a moving traffic violation to Service Oklahoma with a
4 recommendation of suspension of
5 I. No person shall have driving privileges of the defendant
6 until the total amount of any court financial obligation has been
7 paid or waived by the court. Upon receipt of payment of the total
8 amount of the court financial obligations for the moving traffic
9 violation, the court shall send notice thereof to Service Oklahoma,
10 if a nonpayment notice was sent as provided for in this subsection.
11 Notices sent to Service Oklahoma shall be on forms or by a method
12 approved by Service Oklahoma suspended for failure to pay fines,
13 court costs, fees, or assessments.
14 L. J. Every county and district court of this state shall fully
15 utilize and participate in the court cost compliance program. Cases
16 shall be referred to the court cost compliance program no more than
17 sixty (60) days after the court has ordered the referral pursuant to
18 paragraph 4 of subsection G of this section, unless the defendant
19 pays the amount owed on the court financial obligation or an
20 installment due. When the court refers a case, the updated contact
21 information on file shall be forwarded to a court cost compliance
22 liaison for collection purposes.
23 M. K. The Court of Criminal Appeals Administrative Office of
24 the Courts shall implement procedures and develop standardized
ENGR. H. B. NO. 4237 Page 17

1 form s, procedural rules for implementation of the requirements of
2 this section. Such procedures, rules, and any supplemental forms
3 may be made available by the Administrative Office of the Courts,
4 and guidelines to aid courts in conducting ability-to-pay hearings,
5 documenting findings, implementing reductions or waivers, and
6 tracking compliance.
7 L. The provisions of this section shall apply to all sentences
8 imposed on or after November 1, 2026.
9 SECTION 4. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
